fields.description:
When performing a code review, the View menu has provides the ability to select how much context to display around each code change or comment (e.g. 3 Lines, 20 Lines, ... Full Context).

It would be helpful to have an option that expanded the source to show the entire method that encapsulates the code change or comment.

For example, in the following code all lines of the method {{bar()}} would be shown.
{code}
<?php
class foo
{
  private function bar()
  {
    $someCode = 'example';

    // This line is added in the changeset

    $moreCode = 5;
  }
  
  private function notShown()
  {
    // No changes to this method, so it is not displayed
  }
}
{code}

Enter the following comment into a crucible review:

{noformat}!important !! it's bad!{noformat}

It gets rendered as {{null}}

After applying a new formatter to my codebase, I'm seeing the following as a diff

if( condition ){

} 
else if ( condition )

to

if( condition ){

} else if ( condition ){


No whitespace hiding options prevent this from showing up in the diff.

*Premises:*
FishEye 2.7.5
JIRA 4.3.4
JIRA FishEye Plugin 3.1.5

*Summary:*
When trying to create a sub-task in JIRA from a Crucible review, this error is displayed in a popup:
{noformat}
Error creating subtask in JIRA: com.atlassian.jira.rpc.exception.RemotePermissionException: This issue does not exist or you don't have permission to view it.
{noformat}

*What have been tried:*
* Granted all possible project permissions in JIRA side for the user that's logged in both sides;
* Enabled all three authentication methods in the App Links configuration to see if it makes any difference (tried with only Trusted Applications first);
* Checked that the JIRA issue linked in the Crucible review is opened;
* Still get this error.

I'm attaching FishEye logs with extra debugging information for investigation, as well as {{atlassian-jira-security.log}} from JIRA side. {{atlassian-jira.log}} didn't log anything.

From https://sdog.jira.com/browse/JSTDEV-1318

The URL of the avatar image has changed:

* {code}/source/avatar/admin?s=24&s=24{code}
* {code}/source/avatar/admin?s=48?s=24&s=24{code}

Notice the second "?", which breaks internal avatars. Gravatar treats the second "?" as a "&" and works fine.

Seems to happen because of CommentViewDisplay:

{code}
public void setAvatarImageUrl(String url) {
    // The first "?s=" is for the default john doe avatar. The second is the parameter to gravatar's server
    avatar.setUrl(url + "?s=" + AVATAR_SIZE + "&s=" + AVATAR_SIZE);
}
{code}

If an owner of a review is deleted, clicking on the avatar for this deleted user under "author" and "participants" from the review fails with:
{noformat}
The requested resource cannot be found.
user <Username_old1> not found
Referer: http://<Fisheye Base URL>/cru/<Review ID> 
{noformat}

I'm able to create a new review and add a user to it at the same time by using a commit message like this:
{noformat}
My comment +review CR @user1
{noformat}

In this case, the review CR-5 was created, and the user {{user1}} was added as its reviewer.

However, when I try to add another user to this same review, I'm being unable to. 
No errors are thrown in the logs, but nothing was changed in the review as well...

I'm using a commit message like this:
{noformat}
My comment +review CR-5 @user2
{noformat}

According to [this document|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/FISHEYE/Using+Smart+Commits#UsingSmartCommits-IntegrationwithCrucible], this command should work, because I'm entering the review id (CR-5) in the commit message (not only the project key (CR)), meaning that I want to update an existing review instead of creating a new one.

Yes, {{user2}} has the proper permissions set in the CR project.
